WEBVTT

00:08.840 --> 00:12.760
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.380 --> 00:33.660
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.340 --> 00:37.960
And here are your hosts.

00:42.120 --> 00:43.220
This is Daryl Lane.

00:43.320 --> 00:43.940
And Bill Vernon.

00:44.480 --> 00:47.340
You'll sometimes find that collectors of science fiction and fantasy books are into

00:47.340 --> 00:48.020
comics also.

00:48.380 --> 00:52.620
In fact, collecting comics is becoming a more widespread hobby all the time, and often

00:52.620 --> 00:56.300
you'll find collectible comics at a specialty store that handles science fiction, fantasy,

00:56.540 --> 00:57.500
and gaming material.

00:58.100 --> 01:01.900
Bob Wayne owns such a store in Fort Worth, Texas, called Fantastic World's Bookstore,

01:02.060 --> 01:03.220
and he also collects comics.

01:03.600 --> 01:07.320
When he asked him how an interested newcomer might get into comic book collecting, he had

01:07.320 --> 01:08.240
some words of caution.

01:09.100 --> 01:13.580
Well, the first recommendation I make to people is they come in and say, I read that

01:13.580 --> 01:17.960
a so-and-so comic book has gone up a thousand percent in two years.

01:18.440 --> 01:20.760
What comic book would you recommend that I should start collecting?

01:21.620 --> 01:28.220
I tell people that they really shouldn't be buying comics unless they enjoy reading comics.

01:28.900 --> 01:35.160
If there's nothing in that comic that they enjoy reading, then they're making a mistake

01:35.160 --> 01:39.780
getting into comics because there are other things they could invest money in that the

01:40.320 --> 01:43.320
people will not laugh at you when you go to the bank and tell them that you want to use

01:43.320 --> 01:44.020
it for collateral.

01:44.880 --> 01:49.420
So if a comic book has an investment, it's the kind of thing that's really been overplayed

01:49.420 --> 01:50.500
in the media to some extent.

01:50.980 --> 01:54.960
I mean, it sounds real good for the few comics that have appreciated a great deal in value,

01:55.460 --> 01:59.400
but speaking from experience, a bank does not really think that that's the kind of collateral

01:59.400 --> 02:00.800
they want to hold for a loan.

02:00.800 --> 02:05.280
So stocks and bonds still sound preferable to me as investments.

02:05.920 --> 02:08.040
But what if someone did take up comic book collecting?

02:08.380 --> 02:09.800
What about storing and preserving them?

02:10.340 --> 02:19.280
If you're going to keep a kind book for a collection, it's important to handle it carefully,

02:20.460 --> 02:26.180
and if you're going to keep it, you should bag it up, at least in a plastic bag.

02:26.660 --> 02:35.220
If you have a comic book that's worth over $50, $100, you might want to invest in bags

02:36.260 --> 02:40.960
of a type of plastic in which a lot of the things that would be in a plastic that would

02:40.960 --> 02:45.660
potentially cost the comic to an entry rate in 50 or 100 years would be neutralized.

02:46.120 --> 02:49.940
If you want to go further along, if you have comic books that are worth hundreds of dollars,

02:50.400 --> 02:55.220
there are things in the paper, the process of making pulp paper that will eventually

02:55.220 --> 02:55.980
cause it to rot.

02:56.100 --> 03:03.780
You can have this deacidified, but there's no point in doing this with just every comic

03:03.780 --> 03:04.440
book on the shelf.

03:04.920 --> 03:08.940
Actually, if you don't have any errors and you don't plan to be donating these to a

03:08.940 --> 03:13.140
library or something, the comic books that they're handled properly are going to outlive

03:13.140 --> 03:13.980
you most likely.

03:15.040 --> 03:16.900
There's no real danger involved.

03:17.540 --> 03:24.480
They should be kept away from high humidity and excessive extremes of temperature.

03:24.480 --> 03:28.920
They're kept in a dry and cool place and kept out of direct sunlight.

03:34.440 --> 03:38.180
Wayne pointed out to us that there's been a big change in the comic book industry in

03:38.180 --> 03:40.820
the past few years, one that will affect collectors.

03:41.880 --> 03:46.360
The biggest thing that's happened in comic books recently, probably the biggest thing

03:46.360 --> 03:52.200
that's happened since comic books began, is that the ownership of some of the characters

03:52.720 --> 03:59.700
is now being held by the individual creators in much the same way that a publisher does

03:59.700 --> 04:02.940
not own a novel by Isaac Asimov.

04:03.040 --> 04:05.000
Isaac Asimov would own the copyright.

04:05.780 --> 04:11.640
Now, comic books are coming out where the writer or the artist or both own the copyright

04:11.640 --> 04:16.360
to the character and the publisher is publishing it for them in the same kind of relationship

04:16.360 --> 04:18.600
that a book publisher has with a novelist.

04:18.600 --> 04:25.700
This is a complete change in the former system of the publisher owning everything, everything

04:25.700 --> 04:30.740
being done on a work for higher basis as though the artist was just coming in and doing the

04:30.740 --> 04:34.440
same type of function as sweeping the floors inside the corporate offices.

04:35.640 --> 04:42.260
This is going to be a change, it's going to become more and more evident in the next

04:42.260 --> 04:46.580
few years and it's going to create a lot of more excitement within the comic book field.

04:47.180 --> 04:50.060
We'll talk more about comics with Bob Wayne on our next show.

04:57.100 --> 05:01.480
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science

05:01.480 --> 05:05.680
Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

05:45.160 --> 05:46.560
Thank you.

