06:09.260 --> 06:14.500
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:17.380 --> 06:18.820
And here are your hosts.

06:22.860 --> 06:24.740
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

06:24.920 --> 06:28.680
We're talking with Bob Wayne, comic book collector and owner of the Fantastic World's Bookstore

06:28.680 --> 06:29.660
in Fort Worth, Texas.

06:30.420 --> 06:32.320
Comic book collecting has become a rage recently.

06:32.640 --> 06:36.500
The prices of some collectible comics have risen almost 1000% in just a few years.

06:36.680 --> 06:40.560
On our last show, Bob Wayne explained some things about comic book collecting and advised

06:40.560 --> 06:43.860
the unwary newcomer to be extremely cautious when entering the field.

06:43.860 --> 06:47.920
He also mentioned a big change that's taken place recently in the publishing of comic books.

06:48.400 --> 06:52.800
The one who creates and draws a strip has complete rights over his work, just like the author of a novel.

06:53.080 --> 06:57.440
This means a comic book artist could change publishing companies and move to where he can get the best contract.

06:58.040 --> 07:01.420
We asked Wayne what this change would mean to collectors and he gave us an interesting answer.

07:02.300 --> 07:04.420
I have to go back a little bit.

07:04.680 --> 07:10.620
The other thing that has changed the comic industry is the change in distribution where, at one time,

07:10.620 --> 07:15.520
all the comic books were pretty much available at 7-Eleven's and drug stores.

07:16.100 --> 07:22.340
And at 7-Eleven bought them from a distributor, the same people used to that handle TV guide and time magazine and such things.

07:23.120 --> 07:27.440
And they got a bundle of comic books in and what they didn't sell, they sent back for credit.

07:28.960 --> 07:32.900
And this meant that the publishers had to print just like on anything else.

07:32.900 --> 07:39.200
They had to print, you know, let's say 500,000 and they sold 200,000 and 300,000 got thrown away.

07:40.720 --> 07:49.320
With the rise of specialty shops that sell comic books and science fiction books, those shops order their comics in a different fashion.

07:49.460 --> 07:54.380
They order them non-returnable. They get a better discount, but they have to keep everything they order.

07:55.520 --> 08:01.740
And it's now to the point where a lot of comic titles are being published only in the non-returnable format.

08:01.740 --> 08:08.120
So if a person is only buying their comic books at a 7-Eleven or in a small town that doesn't have a specialty store,

08:08.540 --> 08:10.640
there are a number of titles they would never have seen.

08:11.100 --> 08:20.200
In fact, there are titles that are being published only for specialty store distribution that are selling better than some of the comic books that have distribution in both forms.

08:20.740 --> 08:29.580
Examples of this would be Camelot 3000 from DC Comics, which takes the King Arthur saga, brings it back to life, but in the year 3000.

08:29.580 --> 08:38.940
Star Slayer from Pacific Comics just moving to another company called First Comics, which takes a man from out of the past and springs him into the future,

08:39.460 --> 08:44.380
where he goes around and finds alien menaces and zooms from galaxy to galaxy.

08:45.460 --> 08:49.340
These titles are only published in specialty stores.

08:49.340 --> 08:57.260
And the thing with the book like Star Slayer, which is written and drawn by Mike Grell, who used to work for DC Comics doing The Warlord,

08:57.660 --> 09:00.760
is that Mike Grell owns the copyright to Star Slayer.

09:02.080 --> 09:10.460
And the fact that Mike Grell owns the copyright means that when his contract with the publisher Pacific Comics expired with issue number 6,

09:10.460 --> 09:17.940
he was able to find a better deal and make more money from himself and take it to First Comics, a new publishing company out of Chicago,

09:18.680 --> 09:20.420
for starting with issue number 7.

09:31.460 --> 09:36.620
Wayne says this change, which allows a comic book character to switch publishing companies, is a very recent one,

09:36.620 --> 09:39.760
and he likens it to the situation that exists in book publishing.

10:00.840 --> 10:04.940
Some of the ramifications of this new situation should be obvious to collectors.

10:04.940 --> 10:11.440
One difference may well be that a collector devoted to a particular character or artist will have to follow him through a number of publishing companies.

10:11.900 --> 10:16.360
Perhaps a collector will be required to buy more issues too in order to acquire a complete set of something.

10:16.960 --> 10:22.780
Also, it should be more difficult to locate and catalog characters and artists, since they will probably be spread out over more companies.

10:23.120 --> 10:27.460
But for dedicated comic book collectors, the new situation may be a beneficial one after all.

10:27.740 --> 10:33.220
Sure, with more competition, there will likely be more comics and more artists, and therefore more material for collectors to work with.

