12:11.700 --> 12:16.000
Poetry and science fiction, two unlikely candidates for a merger, but they go together very well.

12:16.160 --> 12:19.920
As practitioners of the art and members of the Science Fiction Poetry Association will tell you.

12:20.120 --> 12:26.260
The Science Fiction Radio Show spoke with some people in the Science Fiction Poetry Association about what exactly Science Fiction Poetry is.

12:26.260 --> 12:30.860
Gene Van Troyer, Science Fiction Author and Editor of a mainstream literary magazine, responds.

12:31.660 --> 12:33.080
Well, it's been around for quite a while.

12:33.300 --> 12:37.980
It's only been really in recent years that the term Science Fiction Poetry came into usage.

12:38.120 --> 12:45.700
I think about 1974 was when the term was first used and it was coined by, well, it wasn't coined by anybody,

12:45.880 --> 12:54.800
but it was just used as a label by Peter Dillingham, who was an early prosodist and theorist of Science Fiction Poetry.

12:54.800 --> 13:04.240
And Stephen Gregg, who edited Eternity Science Fiction, which was the first Science Fiction magazine to really incorporate poetry as an integral part of its format.

13:05.240 --> 13:06.760
What is Science Fiction Poetry?

13:07.480 --> 13:15.300
Well, I really can't say what Science Fiction Poetry is in terms of a definition because no one has ever defined science fiction or poetry.

13:15.800 --> 13:18.040
So Science Fiction Poetry has no real definition.

13:18.040 --> 13:28.820
But I generally tend to class Science Fiction Poetry as something containing an element which is usually associated with Science Fiction.

13:29.480 --> 13:36.100
In other words, a speculative element of outer space or of biology or of time or whatnot.

13:36.660 --> 13:38.880
So that's my loose definition.

13:39.460 --> 13:47.160
It's important to realize that what we now are calling Science Fiction Poetry has been written in the so-called mainstream for a long time.

13:47.160 --> 13:56.380
William Blake is a really primary example of someone who wrote mystical poetry, but in order to do it, he created alternate worlds

13:56.380 --> 14:06.800
and an ability to travel between this world or the world of London that he knew and his imaginary England, which he called Albion.

14:07.380 --> 14:14.380
Well, that's fantasy. That's Science Fiction. That's alternate world imagination.

14:16.360 --> 14:24.940
In more modern times, there's W. H. Auden, who has written a number of poems which would be scientifically oriented as well as Science Fiction Poetry

14:24.940 --> 14:31.100
because they speculate about eventual results of scientific discoveries.

14:31.820 --> 14:40.640
One of the most striking examples of what I would call Science Fiction Poetry is something that was done by Richard Wilbur, a well-established mainstream poet.

14:40.640 --> 14:47.800
This poem is called The Mind Reader. This is a poem about a person who actually reads minds and he makes his living by reading minds.

14:48.640 --> 14:56.300
Now, I don't think Richard Wilbur would call it Science Fiction, although maybe in the back of his mind he's working with the idea that, well, this is usually a Science Fiction theme.

14:56.680 --> 14:58.500
But it's really a very well-done poem.

14:59.380 --> 15:08.300
The point about Science Fiction Poetry and mainstream poetry is that to be a good poem, a Science Fiction Poem must first be a good poem.

15:08.300 --> 15:16.000
And then content-wise, it diverges from what we normally recognize or would normally class as mainstream poetry.

15:25.060 --> 15:33.980
The Science Fiction Poetry Association was founded in 1978 by Suzette Hayden Elgin, a mainstream novelist, who saw there was no meeting point for poets in the Science Fiction field.

15:33.980 --> 15:43.060
There are a number of well-known Science Fiction writers who are members of the Science Fiction Poetry Association. Theodore Sturgeon, Ursula Le Guin, Gregory Benford, Ed Bryant, and Gene Wolfe are a few.

15:43.640 --> 15:49.460
We asked Bob Frazier, editor of the Science Fiction Poetry Association newsletter, to tell us what the newsletter accomplishes.

15:50.020 --> 16:00.120
At the moment, the newsletter seems to be the focus of the organization because we don't have any great amount of business that is important to us.

16:00.120 --> 16:16.480
We're sort of like a very small, non-profit organization, just basically people getting to know each other and setting up workshops at conventions, doing readings, teaching each other a little bit about poetry, helping each other find good markets.

16:17.260 --> 16:19.940
We'll talk more about poetry and science fiction on our next show.

